<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-11-18">
  <title>Resources for 11/18</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Recognize what a <em>polynomial function</em> <m>f(x)</m> approaches as <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Recognize what a polynomial function <m>f(x)</m> approaches as <m>x \rightarrow -\infty</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-power-function">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Power Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>power functions</em> and their end behavior. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="mLoKn7kSQp0" />

    <problem>
      <title>Power Function End Behavior (Not on Quiz)</title>
      <p>
        The following problems are to help you understand the end behavior of power functions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Consider the function <m>f(x)=x^n</m>.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Use Desmos to graph <m>f(x)</m> for <m>n=1,2,3,4,5,6</m>.  Determine the end behavior in each case.  In other words, describe what happens to <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m> and as <m>x \rightarrow -\infty</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Determine rules for the end behavior of <m>f</m> that apply to all values of <m>n</m>, where <m>n</m> is a whole number.  Your rules may depend on what type of number <m>n</m> is.  Justify your rule analytically/algebraically.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Consider the function <m>g(x) = ax^n</m>, where <m>a</m> is a real number with <m>a \ne 0</m>.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Do the same as #1(a), except also with <m>a=2</m> and then <m>a=-3</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Come up with a rule for the end behavior of <m>g</m> that works for all values of <m>a</m>.  Justify your rule analytically/algebraically.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What happens if <m>a=0</m>?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Consider the function <m>f(x)=ax+b</m>, <m>a \ne 0</m>.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Use some examples and Desmos to determine a rule for the end behavior of <m>f</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Give an analytical/algebraic reason that justifies the rule you devised above.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-poly-end-behavior">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Polynomial End Behavior</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on the end behavior of <em>polynomials</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="7HI-K7weJQs" />

    <problem>
      <title>Polynomial End Behavior (Not on Quiz)</title>
      <p>
        For each of the following, determine what happens to the function as <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m> and as <m>x \rightarrow -\infty</m>.  Explain what this means about what the graph looks like.  Note that <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, and <m>d</m> are all constants.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=ax^2+bx+c</m>.  Hint:  The answer will depend on <m>a</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x) = ax^3+bx^2+cx+d</m>.  Hint:  Factor out <m>x^3</m> from every term.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x) = ax^4+bx^3+cx^2+dx+e</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x) = ax^5+bx^4+cx^3+dx^2+ex+f</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use your observations above to determine the end behavior of <m>f(x) = -2(x-a)(x-b)(x-c)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

